06829nam a22007575i 9780774855372DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748553727 a10.59962/97807748553722doi  a(DE-B1597)662269  a(OCoLC)1097166291  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL86.P64 ǂb C75 2007eb 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a320.6097100aCritical Policy Studies /ced. by Miriam Smith, Michael Orsini. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b10 b&w figures and tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tCritical Policy Studies -- tPolitical Economy -- tPolitical Economy and Canadian Public Policy -- tPolicy Analysis in an Era of “Globalization”: Capturing Spatial Dimensions and Scalar Strategies -- tCitizens and Diversity -- tCitizen Engagement: Rewiring the Policy Process -- tQueering Public Policy: A Canadian Perspective -- tGender Mainstreaming in the Canadian Context: “One Step Forward and Two Steps Back” -- tPolitical Science, Race, Ethnicity, and Public Policy -- tDiscourse and Knowledge -- tGovernmentality and the Shifting Winds of Policy Studies -- tAgenda-Setting and Issue Definition -- tScientists, Government, and “Boundary Work”: The Case of Reproductive Technologies and Genetic Engineering in Canada -- tBetween Respect and Control: Traditional Indigenous Knowledge in Canadian Public Policy -- tFraming Environmental Policy: Aboriginal Rights and the Conservation of Migratory Birds -- tRisky Subjects -- tFrom the Welfare State to the Social Investment State: A New Paradigm for Canadian Social Policy? -- tCanadian Post-9/11 Border Policy and Spillover Securitization: Smart, Safe, Sovereign? -- tThe Permanent-Emergency Compensation State: A “Postsocialist” Tale of Political Dystopia -- tDiscourses in Distress: From “Health Promotion” to “Population Health” to “You Are Responsible for Your Own Health” -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditional definitions of public policy in Canada have been challenged in recent years by globalization, the transition to a knowledge-based economy, and the rise of new technologies. Critical Policy Studies describes how new policy problems such as border screening and global warming have been catapulted onto the agenda in the neo-liberal era. The book also surveys the recent evolution of critical approaches to policy studies, which have transformed decades-old issues. Contributors conceptualize the ways in which public policy questions cut across the traditional fields of policy. They cover both topical approaches such as Foucauldian and post-empiricist analysis and new applications of established perspectives, such as political economy. Conventional methodologies reveal new connotations when used to explore such topics as security issues, Canadian sovereignty, welfare reform, environmental protocol, Aboriginal policy, and reproductive technologies. Critical Policy Studies provides an alternative to existing approaches to policy studies, and will be welcomed by scholars, students, and practitioners of political science and public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAbele, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbu-Laban, Yasmeen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraefe, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankivsky, Olena, ec